In the first two months of 2020, China's import and export figures showed a double decline, with exports falling several times as fast as imports, due to the new pneumonia epidemic and the extended Chinese New Year holiday.

According to data released by the General Administration of Customs on March 7, from January to February 2020, China's total value of imports and exports of goods denominated in Renminbi was 4,123.76 billion yuan, down 9.6 percent year on year, growth was down 10.3 percentage points from a year earlier (0.7 per cent) . Of this total, exports of 2,040.58 billion yuan decreased by 15.9% year-on-year, a 16 percentage point decrease compared with the same period last year (0.1%) ; imports of 2,083.17 billion yuan decreased by 2.4% year-on-year, a 3.8 percentage point decrease compared with the same period last year (1.4%) ; trade balance-42.59 billion yuan, the trade balance (309.8 billion yuan) decreased by 352.39 billion yuan over the same period last year.

In january-february 2020, the total value of China's goods trade in US dollars was US $591.99 billion, down 11.0% year-on-year and down 7.1 percentage points from the same period last year (- 3.9%) . Of this total, exports fell 17.2 percent to us $292.45 billion, down 12.6 percent from the same period last year (- 4.6 percent) , and imports fell 4.0 percent to us $299.54 billion, down 0.8 percent from the same period last year (- 3.2 percent)  TRADE BALANCE-US $7.10 billion, US $50.98 billion less than the same period last year (US $43.88 billion) . China's import and export data in US dollars are translated at the converted exchange rates published by the State Administration of Foreign Exchange on a monthly basis.

Overall, China's exports of goods in the first two months of this year were heavily affected by the new pneumonia outbreak. Total exports in people's terms fell by 15.9 per cent year-on-year and total exports in US dollars fell by 17.2 per cent year-on-year. Imports of goods were relatively less affected by the outbreak. Imports fell only slightly in the first two months of the year because of the resilience and inertia of China's economy and trade, as well as the timing of commodity shipments and the pace of imports by companies, the General Administration of Customs said.

Han Jian, a professor at Nanjing University Business School, told Caijing that many companies'cash flows had been put to the test by the outbreak, which squeezed orders in February. He suggested that the import and export administrative departments should focus on the "three stability" on the basis of stable foreign trade, namely stable order, stable production and stable logistics.

According to the monitoring of customs data, the import and export value of foreign trade increased by ten days in February, and the amount of customs declaration by enterprises increased by ten days. According to its survey of 2552 sample enterprises, 80.6 percent of the enterprises have resumed work. With the positive results of the epidemic prevention and control, and the gradual implementation of various policies and measures, the pace of resumption of foreign trade enterprises to resume production has accelerated, market confidence is also steadily recovering.

In addition, the volume of China's import and export cargo increased by 2.8 percent year-on-year in terms of weight (10,000 tons) from January to February 2020, according to cargo data released by the General Administration of Customs on the 7th, however, the total number of inbound and outbound means of transport under customs supervision decreased by 40.8% year-on-year, including inbound and outbound vehicles (vehicles) down by 45% year-on-year, inbound and outbound trains (sections) down by 2.2% year-on-year, and inbound and outbound vessels (vessels) down by 20.2% year-on-year, number of inbound and outbound aircraft decreased-27.8% .

By country (region) , from January to February 2020, China's imports and exports to the European Union, the United States and Japan and other traditional trading partners declined, while its imports and exports to ASEAN increased from a year earlier. Specifically: China's imports and exports to ASEAN amounted to 594.11 billion yuan, up 2 percent, accounting for 14.4 percent of China's total foreign trade value. ASEAN has become China's largest trading partner, of which China's exports to ASEAN fell by 3.6 percent, while imports from ASEAN rose by 9 percent China's total trade with the EU fell 14.2% to 557.42 billion yuan, accounting for 13.5% of China's total trade value. The EU (excluding the UK) is China's second largest trading partner, of which China's exports to the EU fell 17.1% and imports from the EU fell 9.9%  The total value of china-us trade was 422.5 billion yuan, down 19.6 percent and accounting for 10.2 percent of China's total foreign trade value. The United States is China's third largest trading partner. Of this total, China's exports to the United States fell 26.5 percent, while imports from the United States rose 4.3 percent. The total value of china-japan trade was 274.95 billion yuan, japan was the fourth largest trading partner, with exports to Japan down 23.3 percent and imports from Japan down 8 percent.

It is worth noting that in the first two months of this year, China's exports of goods to its top four trading partners all declined from a year earlier, with exports to the United States, Japan and the European Union falling by 26.5% , 23.3% and 17.1% respectively, a sharp decline, exports to ASEAN fell by a relatively small 3.6 per cent.

According to the types of enterprises, from January to February 2020, the import and export of goods from private enterprises, foreign-invested enterprises and state-owned enterprises all showed negative growth year on year, and the import and export of foreign-invested enterprises declined even more (- 13.8%) . In terms of export product types, exports of labor-intensive products such as electromechanical products and textiles and garments fell in the first two months of the year. From January to February 2020, China's exports of mechanical and electrical products fell by 14.9 percent, accounting for 58.8 percent of the total value of exports, of which exports of automatic data processing equipment and its components fell by 26 percent and mobile phones by 14.2 percent. Over the same period, exports of clothing and textiles fell by 18.7 per cent, those of plastic products by 14.8 per cent, those of furniture by 21.6 per cent, those of shoes and boots by 18.8 per cent, those of bags and cases by 17.4 per cent and those of toys by 25.7 per cent. In addition, steel exports fell by 27 per cent and automotive (including chassis) exports increased by 0.5 per cent.

In the first two months of this year, imports of iron ore, crude oil, natural gas, soybeans and other commodities increased and the average import price of commodities rose and fell. From January to February 2020, China's imports of iron ore increased by 1.5 percent and the average import price rose by 17.5 percent; Imports of crude oil increased by 5.2 percent and the average import price rose by 10.9 percent; imports of coal increased by 33.1 percent and the average import price fell by 4 percent; and imports of natural gas increased by 2.8 percent, the average import price decreased by 16.9% , while imports of soybeans increased by 14.2% and the average import price decreased by 7.2% . In addition, imports of mechanical and electrical products decreased by 6.1% , of which the number of imported integrated circuits increased by 26.2% and the value increased by 6.8% , while the number of imported automobiles (including chassis) decreased by 11.3% and the value decreased by 4.5% .

Regarding China's import and export trade situation in the next phase, the General Administration of Customs said that although the new pneumonia outbreak will have a certain impact on foreign trade imports and exports in the short term, China's foreign trade development is resilient, the Enterprise's adaptability and market development ability are also very strong, the impact of the epidemic on the import and export is temporary and phased, the long-term trend of foreign trade development has not changed.

At present, the General Administration of Customs has issued a number of policies and measures to ensure the zero-delay customs clearance of epidemic prevention and control materials, deal with the impact of the epidemic, promote steady growth in foreign trade, and support the development of china-europe train and comprehensive bonded areas, we will give full support to foreign trade enterprises to resume work and production and maintain steady growth in foreign trade. During the epidemic, enterprises are also actively negotiating with foreign parties to extend the delivery period, work overtime to complete order tasks.

The head of several export-oriented manufacturing enterprises said that as long as the epidemic is basically under control by the end of March, the negative impact of exports will last until June at the most, and the second half of the year is likely to return to the original balance level.
